{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488440"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.03,0.84,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91959"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"11442"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31541"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a fall where she tripped on the edge of a carpet. She denies any preceding symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her left leg is shortened and externally rotated. Her peripheral pulses are strong and her legs are warm to touch. There is no obvious haematoma. She is tender over the left lateral thigh but not in the pelvis. A hip/pelvis X-ray shows a complete fracture line through the junction of the head and neck of femur with partial displacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is this woman most at risk of?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fat embolus","Compartment syndrome","Deep vein thrombosis","Avascular necrosis of the femoral head","Malunion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman has suffered a subcapital neck of femur (NOF) fracture. The vascular supply to the femoral head arises predominantly from the medial and lateral femoral circumflex arteries, with the ascending arteries attached to the femoral neck. As such, the ascending arteries are easily damaged in the case of an intracapsular NOF fracture, leading to \u003Cstrong\u003Eavascular necrosis of the femoral head\u003C/strong\u003E. The risk of avascular necrosis (AVN) of the femoral head ranges from 10% in intertrochanteric fractures to as high as 90% in trans-epiphyseal fractures. Subcapital fractures, as in this case, are associated with a 50% risk of AVN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst all the listed options could occur after a fractured neck of femur, in terms of frequency, the most common complication would be an avascular necrosis of the femoral head. Fat embolism may occur in up to 10% of long bone fractures, but in less than 1% of femoral neck fractures. This patient only has partial displacement, where malunion is unlikely. In all cases of displacement, the incidence of malunion is about 7%. The incidence of an acute compartment syndrome is less than 1% and vascular injuries are more typically associated with fractures of the femoral shaft.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Avascular necrosis of the femoral head is a well recognised complication of femoral neck fractures.","Intracapsular neck of femur fractures disrupt the blood supply to the femoral head, increasing the risk of avascular necrosis.","Prompt recognition and management of femoral neck fractures are essential to minimise long-term complications."],"references":["Barton\u00edcek J. Proximal femur fractures: the pioneer era of 1818 to 1925. (2004) Clinical orthopaedics and related research.Barton\u00edcek J. Proximal femur fractures: the pioneer era of 1818 to 1925. Clin Orthop Relat Res. 2004 Feb;(419):306-10. PMID: 15021169. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15021169/","Kazley J, Bagchi K. Femoral Neck Fractures. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537347/","Konarski W, Pobo\u017cy T, \u015aliwczy\u0144ski A, Kotela I, Krakowiak J, Hordowicz M, Kotela A. Avascular Necrosis of Femoral Head-Overview and Current State of the Art. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2022 Jun 15;19(12):7348. doi: 10.3390/ijerph19127348. PMID: 35742595; PMCID: PMC9223442. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9223442/","Konarski W, Pobo\u017cy T, Kotela A, \u015aliwczy\u0144ski A, Kotela I, Hordowicz M, Krakowiak J. The Risk of Avascular Necrosis Following the Stabilization of Femoral Neck Fractures: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2022 Aug 15;19(16):10050. doi: 10.3390/ijerph191610050. PMID: 36011686; PMCID: PMC9408780. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36011686/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91959"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91959"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T09:19:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T09:19